messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

Full path
- /api/products/{id}

All HTTP methods accepted?
- all: false

Per-method acceptance (based on the code)
- HEAD: false
- POST: false
- OPTIONS: false
- TRACE: false
- GET: true
- PUT: true
- DELETE: true
- PATCH: false

Explanation
- server.js mounts the product router at the prefix /api/products: app.use('/api/products', productRoutes).
- routes/productRoutes.js defines router.route('/:id') with handlers for .get, .put and .delete:
  - .get(checkObjectId, getProductById) -> GET /api/products/:id is handled (getProductById).
  - .put(protect, admin, checkObjectId, updateProduct) -> PUT /api/products/:id is handled.
  - .delete(protect, admin, checkObjectId, deleteProduct) -> DELETE /api/products/:id is handled.
- No explicit handlers for HEAD, POST, OPTIONS, TRACE, PATCH, or a router/app-wide .all are present in the code, so those methods are marked false (the decision follows the code only, not runtime framework behavior).
- Notes about middleware:
  - GET uses checkObjectId middleware before getProductById.
  - PUT and DELETE require protect and admin middleware (and checkObjectId) before reaching their controllers.
- The documented controller comments also show the intended routes: GET /api/products/:id, PUT /api/products/:id, DELETE /api/products/:id.
